{
  "doc_id": "30402",
  "text": "The present results indicated that inflammation may be an important mechanism underlying the difference in function and number of EPCs isolated from healthy individuals and diabetic patients. EPCs have long been regarded as a potential therapy to accelerate re-endothelialization of impaired vessels. Elevated IL8 expression is also thought to be involved in the repair progress [CITATION_1] . Compared to the successful preclinical results, the results of clinical trials on the efficacy parameters are conflicting [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Certain studies indicated no beneficial effect of autologous EPC transplantation in diabetic patients with critical limb ischemia [CITATION_4] . The controversy may be attributed to the heterogeneity of survival and different sources of EPCs in these trials [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The present results revealed that inflammatory responses and associated genes may be partially involved in the abnormal function and number of EPCs in patients with diabetes.",
